{"type":"message","id":"aec45210","parentId":"f60d2f07","timestamp":"2026-05-28T07:02:34.401Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_cpAAfDjiokGvuH45xgyZ0689","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:309:- Set `hooks.allowedAgentIds` to limit which effective agent a hook can target, including the default agent when `agentId` is omitted.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/policy.md:186:currently require `agentIds`, and that selector supports only `tools.*` and\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/reference/memory-config.md:469:| `store.path`          | `string` | `~/.openclaw/memory/{agentId}.sqlite` | Index location (supports `{agentId}` token) |\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/system-prompt.md:100:`sessions_spawn`. This is prompt-only; tool policy still controls whether\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:20:| `sessions_spawn`   | Spawn an isolated sub-agent session for background work                     |\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:27:set, including `sessions_spawn`, `sessions_yield`, and `subagents`.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:37:    alsoAllow: [\"sessions_spawn\", \"sessions_yield\", \"subagents\"],\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:48:`sessions_list` returns sessions with their key, agentId, kind, channel, model,\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:50:`node`), exact `label`, exact `agentId`, search text, or recency\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:133:`sessions_spawn` creates an isolated session for a background task by default.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:152:`sessions_spawn`, `subagents`, `sessions_list`, and `sessions_history` so they\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:11:An **agent** here is the full per-persona scope: workspace files, auth profiles, model registry, and session store. `agentDir` is the on-disk state directory that holds this per-agent config at `~/.openclaw/agents/<agentId>/`. A **binding** maps a channel account (e.g. a Slack workspace or a WhatsApp number) to one of those agents.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/agent-workspace.md:111:- `~/.openclaw/agents/<agentId>/agent/codex-home/` (per-agent Codex runtime account, config, skills, plugins, and native thread state)\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:644:    **Per-topic agent routing**: Each topic can route to a different agent by setting `agentId` in the topic config. This gives each topic its own isolated workspace, memory, and session. Example:\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/channels/slack.md:1025:- OpenClaw seeds an eligible top-level channel root into `agent:<agentId>:slack:channel:<channelId>:thread:<rootTs>` when that root is expected to start a visible Slack thread, so the root and later thread replies share one OpenClaw session. This applies to `app_mention` events, explicit bot or configured mention-pattern matches, and `requireMention: false` channels with non-`off` `replyToMode`.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq-first-run.md:739:    Yes, via **multi-agent routing**. Bind each sender's WhatsApp **DM** (peer `kind: \"direct\"`, sender E.164 like `+15551234567`) to a different `agentId`, so each person gets their own workspace and session store. Replies still come from the **same WhatsApp account**, and DM access control (`channels.whatsapp.dmPolicy` / `channels.whatsapp.allowFrom`) is global per WhatsApp account. See [Multi-Agent Routing](/concepts/multi-agent) and [WhatsApp](/channels/whatsapp).\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/prose.md:122:| Spawn session / Task tool | `sessions_spawn` |\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/slash-commands.md:443:      - Discord: `agent:<agentId>:discord:slash:<userId>`\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/slash-commands.md:444:      - Slack: `agent:<agentId>:slack:slash:<userId>` (prefix configurable via `channels.slack.slashCommand.sessionPrefix`)\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/exec-approvals.md:419:- If the caller changes `command`, `rawCommand`, `cwd`, `agentId`, or `sessionKey` after the approval request was created, the gateway rejects the forwarded run as an approval mismatch.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/diffs.md:219:    - `context` (`agentId`, `sessionId`, `messageChannel`, `agentAccountId` when available)\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/multi-agent-sandbox-tools.md:24:Auth is scoped by agent: each agent has its own `agentDir` auth store at `~/.openclaw/agents/<agentId>/agent/auth-profiles.json`. Never reuse `agentDir` across agents. Agents can read through to the default/main agent's auth profiles when they do not have a local profile, but OAuth refresh tokens are not cloned into secondary agent stores. If you copy credentials manually, copy only portable static `api_key` or `token` profiles.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/multi-agent-sandbox-tools.md:67:          \"agentId\": \"family\",\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/multi-agent-sandbox-tools.md:328:        \"sessions\": { \"visibility\": \"tree\" },\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/multi-agent-sandbox-tools.md:390:    - Verify with logs: `[tools] filtering tools for agent:${agentId}`.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/subagents.md:5:  - You are changing sessions_spawn or sub-agent tool policy\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/subagents.md:12:They run in their own session (`agent:<agentId>:subagent:<uuid>`) and,\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/subagents.md:65:Agents start background sub-agents with `sessions_spawn`. Sub-agent completions\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/subagents.md:71:    - `sessions_spawn` is non-blocking; it returns a run id immediately.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/subagents.md:105:    - For persistent thread-bound sessions, use `sessions_spawn` with `thread: true` and `mode: \"session\"`."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":61,"aggregated":"/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:309:- Set `hooks.allowedAgentIds` to limit which effective agent a hook can target, including the default agent when `agentId` is omitted.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/policy.md:186:currently require `agentIds`, and that selector supports only `tools.*` and\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/reference/memory-config.md:469:| `store.path`          | `string` | `~/.openclaw/memory/{agentId}.sqlite` | Index location (supports `{agentId}` token) |\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/system-prompt.md:100:`sessions_spawn`. This is prompt-only; tool policy still controls whether\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:20:| `sessions_spawn`   | Spawn an isolated sub-agent session for background work                     |\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:27:set, including `sessions_spawn`, `sessions_yield`, and `subagents`.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:37:    alsoAllow: [\"sessions_spawn\", \"sessions_yield\", \"subagents\"],\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:48:`sessions_list` returns sessions with their key, agentId, kind, channel, model,\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:50:`node`), exact `label`, exact `agentId`, search text, or recency\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/concepts/session-tool.md:133:`sessions_spawn` creates an isolated session for a background task by default.\n/usr/local/lib/node_mo